{"id":"2107.06312","submitter":"Marco Scarsini","authors":"Frederic Koessler, Marco Scarsini, and Tristan Tomala","title":"Convergence and Correlation in Large Games","comments":"24 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.GT econ.TH","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider multi-population Bayesian games with a large number of players.\nEach player aims at minimizing a cost function that depends on her own action,\nthe distribution of players' actions in all populations, and an unknown state\nparameter. We study the nonatomic limit versions of these games. We introduce\nthe concept of Bayes correlated Wardrop equilibrium, which extends the concept\nof Bayes correlated equilibrium to nonatomic games. We prove that Bayes\ncorrelated Wardrop equilibria are limits of action flows induced by Bayes\ncorrelated equilibria of the game with a large finite set of small players. For\nnonatomic games with complete information admitting a convex potential, we\nprove that the set of correlated and of coarse correlated Wardrop equilibria,\nare reduced to the set of probability distributions over Wardrop equilibria,\nand that all equilibrium outcomes have the same costs. We get the following\nconsequences. First, all flow distributions of (coarse) correlated equilibria\nin convex potential games with finitely many players converge to Wardrop\nequilibria when the weight of each player tends to zero. Second, for any\nsequence of flows satisfying no-regret property, its empirical distribution\nconverges to the set of distributions over Wardrop equilibria and the average\ncost converges to the unique Wardrop cost.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:13:40 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 26 Sep 2022 18:48:12 GMT"},{"version":"v3","created":"Thu, 2 Feb 2023 06:46:24 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-02-03"}
