{"id":"2107.06331","submitter":"Rahul Chandan","authors":"Rahul Chandan, Dario Paccagnan and Jason R. Marden","title":"The Unintended Consequences of Minimizing the Price of Anarchy in\n  Congestion Games","comments":"34 pages, 3 figures, 1 table","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"cs.GT cs.SY eess.SY","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  This work focuses on the design of taxes in atomic congestion games, a\ncommonly studied model for competitive resource sharing. While most related\nstudies focus on optimizing either the worst- or best-case performance (i.e.,\nPrice of Anarchy (PoA) or Price of Stability (PoS)), we investigate whether\noptimizing for the PoA has consequences on the PoS. Perhaps surprisingly, our\nresults reveal a fundamental trade-off between the two performance metrics. Our\nmain result demonstrates that the taxation rule that optimizes the PoA inherits\na matching PoS, implying that the best outcome is no better than the worst\noutcome under such a design choice. We then study this trade-off in terms of\nthe Pareto frontier between the PoA and PoS. Our results also establish that\nany taxes with PoS equal to 1 incur a much higher PoA, and that, in several\nwell-studied cases, the untaxed setting lies strictly above the Pareto\nfrontier.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 13 Jul 2021 18:51:46 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Thu, 13 Apr 2023 01:54:04 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-04-14"}
