{"id":"2107.06714","submitter":"Arjun Ramachandra Dr.","authors":"Arjun Ramachandra, Napat Rujeerapaiboon, Melvyn Sim","title":"Robust Conic Satisficing","comments":"46 pages, 4 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.OC","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  In practical optimization, we typically model uncertainty as a random\nvariable though its true probability distribution is unobservable to the\ndecision maker. Historical data provides some information of this distribution\nthat we can use to approximately quantify the risk of an evaluation function\nthat depends on both decision and uncertainty. This empirical optimization is\nvulnerable to the issues of overfitting, which could be overcome by several\ndata-driven robust optimization techniques. To tackle overfitting, Long et al.\n(2022) propose a robust satisficing model, which is specified by a performance\ntarget and a penalty function that measures the deviation of the uncertainty\nfrom its nominal value, and yields solutions with superior out-of-sample\nperformance. We generalize the robust satisficing framework to conic\noptimization problems with recourse, which has broader applications in\npredictive and prescriptive analytics including risk management and statistical\nsupervised learning. We derive an exact semidefinite optimization formulation\nfor biconvex quadratic evaluation function, with quadratic penalty and\nellipsoidal support set. More importantly, under complete and bounded recourse,\nand reasonably chosen polyhedral support set and penalty function, we propose\nsafe approximations that do not lead to infeasible problems for any reasonably\nchosen target. We demonstrate that the assumption of complete and bounded\nrecourse is however not unimpeachable, and then introduce a novel perspective\ncasting technique to derive an equivalent conic optimization problem that\nsatisfies the stated assumptions. Finally, through a computational study on\ndata-driven portfolio optimization (that maximizes the expected exponential\nutility of the portfolio returns), we show that the robust satisficing\nsolutions significantly improve over the celebrated Markowitz model, which is\nprone to overfitting.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 14 Jul 2021 14:00:47 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 29 Apr 2022 10:51:33 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-05-02"}
